Dear Families,



      Well, the end of the year is upon us!  This will be our last
newsletter.

Yesterday, the class helped devise a plan for the Morning Meetings of our
last week of school.  Here is what we came up with:

MONDAY:  Read a story

TUESDAY: Celebrate summer birthdays

WEDNESDAY: =E2=80=9CDrawing Wednesday=E2=80=9D (more info below)

THURSDAY: Work Time Share (more info below)

FRIDAY:    -    Watch End-of-the-year Goodbye Videos

   -

   Read a story
   -

   Graduation Ceremony for 8th Graders


There are just a couple more notes about next week=E2=80=99s plan that pare=
nts
should be aware of:


   -

   MONDAY at 12 NOON: Lunch Bunch with Second Grade Teachers: Eli and I
   will host a =E2=80=9CLunch Bunch=E2=80=9D Zoom session for both first gr=
ade classes.  Liz
   Malerba and Sara Edwards-Auguste, two of the 2nd/3rd grade teachers, wil=
l
   be in attendance.  This meeting will be a chance for kids to ask questio=
ns
   about what to expect in 2nd grade, and to get to know these teachers.  K=
ids
   can have lunch with us at this time; we will =E2=80=9Cchat and chew=E2=
=80=9D!



   -

   =E2=80=9CDrawing Wednesday=E2=80=9D:  This idea was proposed by kids.  W=
ednesday=E2=80=99s
   Morning Meeting will be a time for us to illustrate our fiction stories,=
 or
   do some free drawing.



   -

   Work Time Share Thursday:  Kids can bring a project or activity to
   Morning Meeting to share with their friends.  It could be a craft, a leg=
o
   structure, a game they like to play...or anything, really.  If sending a
   photo for me to screen share would be helpful, feel free to do so!



   -

   Next week, our daily lessons will be slightly abbreviated and there will
   be no lessons/meetings on Friday so that everyone may attend the 8th gra=
de
   graduation (see Valerie=E2=80=99s email for details).


Thank You! (and a bit of reflection)

     Parents and caregivers,  we want to thank you all for your help and
care this year-- for coming on field trips, for lively Family Conferences,
for donating supplies and funding for materials-- all of it helped our year
run smoothly.  And, as we transitioned to home learning-- thank you for
your patience, understanding, encouragement, partnership, and sense of
humor.  Your hard work in taking on the role of teacher and your confidence
and trust as parents gave us the privilege to work with your children in a
way that is profoundly rewarding for us as educators.  Thank you.

     In writing this letter, I am realizing that many of the things I
usually discuss with families at the end of the year simply do not apply!
In the classroom as the year comes to a close, we typically discuss
upcoming transitions into summer and the adventure of a new school year
that lies just beyond.  Because summer plans might still be uncertain, and
the 2020-2021 school year is still very much in flux, these conversations
feel a tad irrelevant.  With that said, we will spend some time next week
talking about changes, growth, and feelings...so many feelings!

     In reflecting about my own feelings about the end of, what will
certainly be remembered as the weirdest school year ever, I have been
thinking about some words spoken to children during our ballet sessions
(way back in the fall).  Jennifer, our ballet teacher, would remind the
class in each session that they are brave and strong.  Back then, we talked
about how it took bravery and strength to share your work (especially when
it comes to getting on a stage).  These days, I have thought of =E2=80=9Cbr=
ave and
strong=E2=80=9D in terms of resilience.  In these less-than-ideal circumsta=
nces,
your children have epitomized these qualities in so many ways.  I invite
you to also reflect back over your child=E2=80=99s year in school, both in =
the
classroom and at home, and to think about the incredible people that they
are, as well as the bravery and strength it takes for six and
seven-year-olds to persevere in this difficult moment.  We are so proud of
them!

Have a nice weekend!  And Happy Father=E2=80=99s Day!

Eleanor, Nita, Shawna, and Luis

